---
import GuideLayout from "../layouts/GuideLayout.astro";
import { guideResources, toolResources } from "../data/content";

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  mainEntity: [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      name: "How do I calculate my current grade?",
      acceptedAnswer: {
        "@type": "Answer",
        text: "If your class uses total points, divide total points earned by total points possible and multiply by 100. If your class uses category weights, multiply each category average by its weight and add the results together."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      name: "What is the difference between points-based grades and weighted grades?",
      acceptedAnswer: {
        "@type": "Answer",
        text: "A points-based grade treats each assignment according to its point value. A weighted grade treats categories such as homework, quizzes, tests, and finals according to the percentage each category counts in the class."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      name: "What is the easiest way to calculate my grade?",
      acceptedAnswer: {
        "@type": "Answer",
        text: "The easiest way is to use a grade calculator. If your class uses total points, use the Grade Calculator. If your class uses category weights, use the Weighted Grade Calculator."
      }
    }
  ]
};

const relatedItems = [
  toolResources.gradeCalculator,
  toolResources.weightedGradeCalculator,
  toolResources.finalExamCalculator,
  toolResources.whatGradeDoINeedCalculator,
  guideResources.howFinalsAffectYourGrade,
];
---

<GuideLayout
  title="How to Calculate Your Grade Step by Step"
  description="Learn how to calculate your current grade step by step with total-points examples, weighted-category examples, common mistakes, and helpful calculators."
  slug="/how-to-calculate-your-grade"
  heroTitle="How to Calculate Your Grade Step by Step"
  heroText="Whether your class uses points, percentages, or weighted categories, you can break your grade into clear steps and check the math with the right calculator."
  faqSchema={faqSchema}
  relatedItems={relatedItems}
>
  <div class="guide-body">
    <section class="card">
      <p>
        Your <strong>current grade</strong> is the class average you have earned so
        far based on the work already counted in the gradebook. The exact formula
        depends on whether your class uses <strong>total points</strong> or
        <strong> weighted categories</strong>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Need a quick answer? Try the <a href="/grade-calculator/">Grade Calculator</a>.
        If your class uses category weights, use the
        <a href="/weighted-grade-calculator/"> Weighted Grade Calculator</a>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Method 1: Total Points</h2>
      <p>
        In a points-based class, you add all the points you earned, divide by all
        the points possible, and convert the result to a percentage.
      </p>
      <p class="formula-block">(points earned / points possible) x 100</p>

      <h3>Total-points example</h3>
      <p>If you earned 420 points out of 500 possible points, your grade is:</p>
      <p>
        420 / 500 = 0.84
        <br />
        0.84 x 100 = 84%
      </p>
      <p>So your current grade is <strong>84%</strong>.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Method 2: Weighted Categories</h2>
      <p>
        In a weighted class, each category counts for a set percentage of the final
        grade. Homework might count less than tests, and the final exam may count a
        lot more than either one.
      </p>

      <h3>Weighted-category example</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Homework: 92% worth 20%</li>
        <li>Quizzes: 85% worth 25%</li>
        <li>Tests: 78% worth 35%</li>
        <li>Final: 90% worth 20%</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Each category contributes this amount to the class grade:</p>
      <p>
        92 x 0.20 = 18.4
        <br />
        85 x 0.25 = 21.25
        <br />
        78 x 0.35 = 27.3
        <br />
        90 x 0.20 = 18
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Total:</strong>
        <br />
        18.4 + 21.25 + 27.3 + 18 = 84.95%
      </p>

      <p>Your weighted grade is <strong>84.95%</strong>.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>When to Use Each Calculator</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Need a quick answer? Try the <a href="/grade-calculator/">Grade Calculator</a>.</li>
        <li>If your class uses category weights, use the <a href="/weighted-grade-calculator/">Weighted Grade Calculator</a>.</li>
        <li>Planning for a final? Use the <a href="/final-exam-calculator/">Final Exam Calculator</a>.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Common Mistakes</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Averaging percentages without checking category weights</li>
        <li>Forgetting that the final exam may be worth a large percentage</li>
        <li>Confusing points-based grades with weighted grades</li>
        <li>Assuming every assignment affects the grade equally</li>
        <li>Not checking the school or teacher's grading policy</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How do I calculate my current grade?</h3>
        <p>Use total points if your class adds assignment scores together, or use weighted averages if each category has a set percentage of the class.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Can I calculate my grade without the final exam?</h3>
        <p>Yes. Your current grade only uses the work that has already been counted. If the final exam has not happened yet, it should not be part of your current grade.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What should I use if I want to know what I need next?</h3>
        <p>Use the <a href="/what-grade-do-i-need-calculator/">What Grade Do I Need Calculator</a> to work backward from your goal.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>
</GuideLayout>
